SIMPLE: trundle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trundle
<hw>Trun"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>tryndel</ets> a little shield. See <er>Trend</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A round body; a little wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lind of low-wheeled cart; a truck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A motion as of something moving upon little wheels
or rollers; a rolling motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A lantern wheel. See
under <er>Lantern</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the bars of a
lantern wheel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trundle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trundle
<hw>Trun"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trundled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trundling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
roll (a thing) on little wheels; <as>as, to <ex>trundle</ex> a bed or a
gun carriage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to roll or revolve; to roll along; <as>as,
to <ex>trundle</ex> a hoop or a ball</as>.</def> <rj><au>R. A.
Proctor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trundle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trundle
<hw>Trun"dle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go or move on
small wheels; <as>as, a bed <ex>trundles</ex> under
another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To roll, or go by revolving, as a hoop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trundle-bed</ent>⟦br⟧
